missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-001/attacks/chain-02.md:5:This chain is attacking the right high-upside question, but it is structurally at risk of confusing an algebraic rewrite with a usable estimate. The central analogy to SQG is weaker than the chain admits: in SQG, the first-order commutator is tied to scalar transport and a linear constitutive law, while in NS the Lamb-vector / vorticity / Helmholtz forms are mostly equivalent repackagings of the same quadratic vector interaction. Unless the chain screens candidates at the level of the actual localized or truncated estimate that matters, it can spend several steps rediscovering textbook identities and then either overclaim a negative result or drift into Chain 03's Beltrami geometry.
missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-001/attacks/chain-02.md:14:- The step risks re-deriving facts the mission already treats as established: scalar truncation survives in SQG, vector truncation does not in NS; the vorticity route still lands at the same `beta = 4/3` barrier; Beltrami cancellation is exact but fragile. If the comparison matrix just restates those points, Step 1 produces paperwork, not progress.
missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-001/attacks/chain-02.md:27:- Scale counting is not enough. A symbol can look first-order under naive counting and still fail once the relevant truncation, commutator, or nonlocal pressure reconstruction is applied. This step needs estimate-level testing, not just identity-level algebra.
missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-001/attacks/chain-02.md:36:- Testing exact Beltrami flows is a weak stress test for an allegedly generic NS mechanism. Exact Beltrami is a highly nongeneric symmetry class where the Lamb vector vanishes by design. Success there proves almost nothing.
missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-001/attacks/chain-02.md:37:- The mission context already records the crucial negative fact: the Beltrami-based cancellation does not survive even very small perturbations from alignment. That means Step 3 is in danger of rediscovering an established fragility rather than testing a genuinely open point.
missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-001/attacks/chain-02.md:38:- "Small perturbations away from Beltrami alignment" is underspecified. Small in `L^2`, `H^1`, direction field, or a pointwise angle deficit? These are mathematically very different. Without fixing the perturbation metric, the stress test is not interpretable.
missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-001/attacks/chain-02.md:40:- This step overlaps heavily with Chain 03. Once the test object becomes "Beltrami alignment plus perturbations," the chain has drifted from algebraic reformulation into geometry-first fragility analysis. That weakens the claim that Chain 02 is meaningfully distinct.
missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-001/attacks/chain-02.md:42:Concrete failure mode: Step 3 may produce an inequality that looks favorable in an exact or nearly exact Beltrami regime, then collapse outside that regime. At that point the chain has not found an SQG-type mechanism; it has merely recovered the known statement that special alignment depletes the nonlinearity.
missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-001/attacks/chain-02.md:50:- The negative endpoint is too broad relative to the search procedure. "NS has no SQG-type first-order cancellation in any natural formulation tested here" is fair. Stronger language such as "no SQG-style commutator analogue survives the NS vector geometry" is not earned by checking a short list of familiar formulations.
missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-001/attacks/chain-02.md:51:- The step also inherits the contamination from Step 3. If the surviving mechanism is really a near-Beltrami geometry effect, then the chain should close by handing that result to the geometry branch, not by presenting it as an algebraic reformulation win.
missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-001/attacks/chain-02.md:53:Concrete failure mode: Step 4 can produce a memo that sounds definitive while the underlying work only ruled out a handful of obvious rewrites and one nongeneric Beltrami-based pilot.
missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-001/attacks/chain-02.md:68:- Beltrami/Lamb-vector fragility is also already on record.
missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-001/attacks/chain-02.md:69:- Once Step 3 uses Beltrami perturbations, the chain overlaps materially with Chain 03.
missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-001/attacks/chain-02.md:77:- Step 3's kill condition is actually reasonable if the target is a generic NS mechanism, but then it makes the branch nearly predetermined because prior context already says Beltrami cancellation is highly fragile.
missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-001/attacks/chain-02.md:84:The chain is visibly captivated by the SQG analogy. That is useful as a generator of questions, but it can also force NS into a mold that the mission context already says is structurally mismatched: scalar truncation, linear constitutive law, and first-order commutator structure. A fairer framing would be "does NS possess an alternative cancellation mechanism that plays an analogous strategic role?" not "can we find the NS version of the SQG commutator?"
missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-001/attacks/chain-02.md:100:If this chain is kept, it should be treated as a short obstruction-hunting branch, not a full four-step attack path. The honest version is: front-load the Tao filter, demand an estimate-level improvement by the end of Step 2, and stop immediately if the only surviving signal is Beltrami-alignment fragility, because that is geometry-branch material rather than an SQG-type algebraic breakthrough.
